04312nam a22006495i 9780226516752DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017049043  a9780226516752  a(DE-B1597)521309  a(OCoLC)1027206353  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPN1181b.E57 2018 4aPN1181b.E57 2019 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809.103223  aHI 1249qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/49804:1 aEisendrath, Rachel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPoetry in a World of Things :bAesthetics and Empiricism in Renaissance Ekphrasis /cRachel Eisendrath. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b12 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Subjectivity and the Antiquarian Object: Petrarch among the Ruins of Rome -- t3. Here Comes Objectivity: Spenser’s 1590 The Faerie Queene, Book 3 -- t4. Playing with Things: Reification in Marlowe’s Hero and Leander -- t5. Feeling like a Fragment: Shakespeare’s The Rape of Lucrece -- t6. Coda: Make Me Not Object -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe have become used to looking at art from a stance of detachment. In order to be objective, we create a “mental space” between ourselves and the objects of our investigation, separating internal and external worlds. This detachment dates back to the early modern period, when researchers in a wide variety of fields tried to describe material objects as “things in themselves”—things, that is, without the admixture of imagination. Generations of scholars have heralded this shift as the Renaissance “discovery” of the observable world. In Poetry in a World of Things, Rachel Eisendrath explores how poetry responded to this new detachment by becoming a repository for a more complex experience of the world. The book focuses on ekphrasis, the elaborate literary description of a thing, as a mode of resistance to this new empirical objectivity. Poets like Petrarch, Spenser, Marlowe, and Shakespeare crafted highly artful descriptions that recovered the threatened subjective experience of the material world. In so doing, these poets reflected on the emergence of objectivity itself as a process that was often darker and more painful than otherwise acknowledged. This highly original book reclaims subjectivity as a decidedly poetic and human way of experiencing the material world and, at the same time, makes a case for understanding art objects as fundamentally unlike any other kind of objects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEkphrasis. 0aEuropean poetryyRenaissance, 1450-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aPoetry, Moderny15th and 16th centuriesxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aChristopher Marlowe.  aEdmund Spenser.  aFrancesco Petrarch.  aWilliam Shakespeare.  aaesthetics.  aekphrasis.  aempiricism.  aobjectivity.  asubjectivity.  athings.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226516752423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226516752/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles